<ns3292:section xmlns:ns3292="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.networkServices.ntp.client">

	<ns3293:title xmlns:ns3293="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Network Time Client</ns3293:title>
	<ns3294:para xmlns:ns3294="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
	To configure your unix systems time from a NTP server, schedule the following command. <ns3295:emphasis xmlns:ns3295="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="strong">ntpupdate ntphost</ns3295:emphasis>. In many scenarios, the -u and -s flag might become useful. The -u flag uses an unprivileged port (&gt;1024), which can assist when your server is behind a firewall. The -s flag redirects any output to the system syslog facility.
	</ns3294:para>
	<ns3296:programlisting xmlns:ns3296="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
		0	0	*	*	*	/usr/sbin/ntpdate teddy.earth
	</ns3296:programlisting>
</ns3292:section>